# Unity 6.2 Project Rules

## Project Overview

This project uses Unity 6.2 (LTS 2025) with modern systems and architectural approaches.

## Tech Stack

- **Unity Version**: 6.2 LTS (2025)
- **C# Version**: 9.0 (current compiler target in this project)
- **Rendering Pipeline**: URP (Universal Render Pipeline)
- **Input System**: New Input System (InputSystem package)
- **UI Framework**: UI Toolkit (not UGUI)
- **Asset Management**: Addressables

## Architectural Principles

### 1. Modularity
- Each system must be independent
- Use ScriptableObject Architecture for configuration
- Use dependency injection to wire up components

### 2. Performance
- Object pooling for frequently instantiated objects
- Addressables instead of Resources
- ECS/DOTS for performance-critical systems
- Burst Compiler where applicable

### 3. Maintainability
- Strict naming conventions
- XML documentation for public APIs
- Unit tests for business logic
- Prefabs for reusable objects

### 4. Code Style
- Follow the Unity C# Style Guide
- Use modern C# features that are compatible with C# 9.0 (for example pattern matching, records, init-only properties)
- Do not use C# 10+ syntax until the project compiler target is upgraded; avoid file-scoped namespaces and other newer language features
- async/await instead of coroutines where possible

## Supported Platforms

- Windows

## Important Rules

✅ **ALWAYS**:
- New Input System
- UI Toolkit
- Addressables
- [SerializeField] instead of public
- XML documentation

❌ **NEVER**:
- Legacy Input
- UGUI for new UI
- Resources.Load
- FindObjectOfType in Update
- Magic numbers
